WEBVTT

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:06.720
Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you for sticking around for the very last talk of the day here.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:20.240
Okay. Thank you again for coming. My name is Noam Ross. I'm Executive Director of rOpenSci,

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:26.320
and I'm going to be speaking about our rOpenSci Champions program and how we build communities

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:31.760
of open-source leaders. I want to say from the start, I have the privilege of being the

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:35.520
director of an organization, which also means that mostly I get to talk a lot about other

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:41.439
people's work. This work in particular has been led by our spectacular community manager,

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:48.480
Shani Sabine. And so I'll be talking about some of the work that I've done, but the work that

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:54.240
she's very much facilitated through our organization. First, I want to give you a

00:00:54.240 --> 00:01:01.119
little background about rOpenSci, what our goals and values are. rOpenSci was founded in

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:07.680
2011. It's a nonprofit organization. Our goal is to foster a culture that values open,

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:14.320
collaborative, and reproducible research using shared data and reusable methods. And we do that

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:19.680
by building both the technical and social infrastructure in the R language that's

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:27.040
needed to enable that open science in a welcoming and diverse community. And I feel like, you know,

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:32.480
in these times, it's really important to emphasize that last part. The diversity, equity, inclusion,

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:38.959
and accessibility of our community is both a core value of the open science we do, that that science

00:01:38.959 --> 00:01:44.320
is accessible to everybody, and it's a key instrument of our goals, and that we need it

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:52.559
in order to accomplish the science that we want to do. We have a number of different program areas.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:59.360
The first one being software peer review, which we've been doing for 12 years. It's a program

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:05.599
where people can contribute code to be reviewed by peers. We run a number of different sort of

00:02:05.599 --> 00:02:12.160
technological platform programs. The marquee one these days is rUniverse, which is our R package

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:17.600
hosting and publishing platform. We have a number of projects in multilingualism and translation,

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:23.199
providing resources in multiple languages and tools to enable that type of translation, both

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:30.720
guides and packages and automated translation facilitation tools. We run community events,

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:36.720
hackathons, community calls, co-working times to facilitate the community to do our work,

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:40.720
and then finally we do training and mentorship, and that's really what I'm going to focus on today.

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:54.639
So we do all of these things to support open source science. Open source science is a certain

00:02:54.639 --> 00:03:01.199
area of software development with its unique challenges, and people who support open source

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:07.600
scientific projects have a number of challenges that they report when they are managing those

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:13.679
over time. Those challenges are really in the social realm. They have to deal with burnout,

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:18.240
dealing with funding issues, dealing with leadership and community development issues,

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:24.080
stability, how they manage their communities, the internal communication, the external communication.

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:31.440
People report that these are the challenges that cause their software packages and their

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:38.240
projects to stutter and fail over time, and we want to think about how we can facilitate

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.759
overcoming those challenges for scientific developers.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:48.880
Some of the things that, you know, when interviewed, scientific developers have said about

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:54.320
what it takes to sustain their work. They say, I just don't have enough time to do all the things

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:59.360
that I want to do because they require a level of expertise that is difficult to teach, and I

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:04.960
haven't been able to easily recruit people to continue the work. Or it takes longer than a year

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:10.479
to develop people to move into leadership. The hardest part is finding the right person

00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:16.320
and having the time to invest in mentorship. So succession and mentorship, recruiting

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:21.519
co-maintainers are a key challenge to sustaining scientific software.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:29.839
Scientific software also has a problem of scale. Most tools developed in the scientific sphere

00:04:29.839 --> 00:04:36.239
are part of what we call the long tail of scientific software. There are sort of mega packages,

00:04:36.239 --> 00:04:43.519
be they commercial or scientific, the Tidyverse and SciPy, but most tools are small and niche

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:48.559
and essential to specific communities but don't necessarily have the scale of other

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:54.799
open source software packages. They're developed to meet a knowledge need, not necessarily a market,

00:04:54.799 --> 00:05:00.320
so they don't go into a place that has scale. The teams that develop them are often not full-time

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:05.119
developers. They are small and they are splitting their time between development and research.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:11.200
They may have user communities that scale with the success of the project, so the user community

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:18.160
grows, but the funding resources and the size of the team does not necessarily grow with the scale

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:24.399
of the user community, and if that team is small, it doesn't necessarily have the critical mass

00:05:24.399 --> 00:05:30.959
for the learning cultures that, you know, we all learned about this morning from Cat.

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:37.839
So that size is a real challenge, and one thing that we deal with a great deal is that these small

00:05:37.839 --> 00:05:43.760
projects have a high risk of maintainer loss and abandonment because when you're dealing with a

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:51.200
project that has one, two, or three people and they reach a stage of burnout or a new job or a graduation

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:56.320
or other challenges, you have this possibility that you're going to lose a maintainer and the

00:05:56.320 --> 00:06:01.600
remaining maintainers are zero or aren't capable of moving it forward, so a lot of the work we do

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:07.359
in our OpenSci and our broader package developer community is trying to recruit those maintainers

00:06:07.359 --> 00:06:16.000
in, trying to bring someone into a project so that early enough or after the fact so it can

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:23.200
continue when it needs to. So we have many of these challenges. These challenges are heavily driven by

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:30.079
the scale of these software projects. They're small but important. So what do we do when we have a

00:06:30.079 --> 00:06:36.239
challenge of lots of small teams that have a problem of scale by the limits of their size? Well,

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:44.239
there's a book I really liked as a kid about Swimmy, right? Swimmy is the eye of this fish, this fish

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:49.519
right here, and Swimmy's insight, which is the insight that everyone spoke about in this room and

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:55.920
is here as they know, is that you can do things together better that you can't alone, right?

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:02.959
A small fish may not be able to do something that a big fish can, but a lot of small fish can, right?

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:09.519
You make an open source project together, you join a club, you join the community garden, you form a

00:07:09.519 --> 00:07:15.119
union together, you're able to accomplish things together. But when the context, when our unit of

00:07:15.119 --> 00:07:21.440
our small fish is a small software development team, what is the big fish that we form together?

00:07:22.079 --> 00:07:29.200
And that big fish is a community of practice. Community of practices are groups of people who

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:35.119
share a passion for something that they know how to do and who interact regularly in order to learn

00:07:35.119 --> 00:07:40.480
how to do it better, how to support each other. Everyone in this room, in this conference, form

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:47.040
a community of practice of R. R Bensai is working to build communities of practice specific to the

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:53.359
open source scientific challenge. So our question is how do we foster that community of practice

00:07:53.359 --> 00:07:59.600
that has both the social and technical skills needed to sustain that scientific open software?

00:08:00.239 --> 00:08:06.959
All of our programs cover this, but the one that really addresses it most directly

00:08:06.959 --> 00:08:12.959
is our community champions program where we build leaders for open source science, specifically

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:19.839
building those combinations of skills. So the R Bensai champions program is a 12-month

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:29.519
part-time cohort-based fellowship where participants come together to learn those

00:08:29.519 --> 00:08:35.840
skills on contributing to and forming communities of practice, both together and with one-on-one

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:41.760
mentorship from other R Bensai members. So I'll talk a bit about the pieces that

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:45.679
we have for this program and how and why we implement them.

00:08:48.239 --> 00:08:54.320
So the first thing that is the principle of our design of the champions program is to recruit for

00:08:54.320 --> 00:09:00.239
and design for maximum accessibility for historically underrepresented groups. So the

00:09:00.239 --> 00:09:07.280
capacity to do this work is everywhere, but the circumstances where people are able to participate

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:14.080
is not and is the limiting factor. And both because expanding that limiting factor is what's

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:19.599
going to enable us to have more open source scientific maintainers and because expanding

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:25.359
that limiting factor is the moral imperative in open science, we really prioritize making

00:09:25.359 --> 00:09:32.640
sure this program is accessible as broadly as possible. So part of that is a very active

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:39.280
recruitment program where we partner with affinity groups, with local R user groups,

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:45.679
do a great deal of outreach with ambassadors and academics in different parts of the world

00:09:45.679 --> 00:09:51.359
to make sure that people can know about this program, and then we hold information sessions

00:09:51.359 --> 00:09:56.000
during the recruitment phase so people who may not be used to such programs or used to

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.880
applying to such programs can learn about what it means and what they need to do to apply.

00:10:00.960 --> 00:10:07.599
We're very proud of how broad that is able to reach. In our last phase, we had applicants from

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:12.719
the first phase, we had applicants from over 55 countries. I'm not actually sure how many we have

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:20.239
for a more recent one. Then we really prioritize in the design of the project accessibility,

00:10:20.239 --> 00:10:26.960
support, and safety. So accessibility is very broad. One of the accessibility

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:34.479
topics that we think about a lot is language. So while in our first two cohorts were English,

00:10:34.479 --> 00:10:39.679
but we think very carefully about the design of making sure it's broadly accessible in English,

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:44.799
in our cohort this year, we're running our first all Spanish training program. That's going to

00:10:44.799 --> 00:10:49.840
repeat and we're thinking about how do we expand that to focus on more languages and regions.

00:10:50.479 --> 00:10:56.880
This is a supported program. It took a lot of effort to go to funders and say what we wanted

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:01.119
to do is give people stipends to participate because we have heard that that is a really

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:08.000
important step in them being able to spend time from their job at this. So we're able to provide

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:14.960
stipends for this for both participants and in cases where mentors where they need it as well.

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:20.400
And we think about accessibility from a disability's perspective and safety and

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:24.559
making sure that people understand that they have a safe space, they have a code of conduct,

00:11:25.440 --> 00:11:30.640
they have everything they need to be able to participate fully. And then all of those things

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:36.400
are something that we subject to regular inquiry and feedback and multiple times during the course

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:42.559
of the yearlong program we go back to our champions and we say what's working and what's not,

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:47.840
what do you have a challenge to participation that we can work on as well. We focus on that

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:56.320
very heavily. Then the core is that the design of the program is to teach the skills of

00:11:56.320 --> 00:12:02.719
collaborative software development first and that development and maintenance work in the context

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:09.760
of an open source community. So everything we teach is about the collaborative interactive

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:17.119
component of technology development. All of our champions have experience with R, experience

00:12:17.119 --> 00:12:23.039
with data science, lots of career experience in their different fields of expertise. So what we

00:12:23.039 --> 00:12:28.640
really focus on is this participation. So on one hand we cover our package development. That's

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:34.719
something that some learners know and others don't. But it's sort of the core that we build around.

00:12:34.719 --> 00:12:40.159
But then the lessons that we work on are on building software together which are essentially

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:45.679
team collaboration techniques. We talk about code style best practices. How do you develop so

00:12:45.679 --> 00:12:51.599
something is readable and maintainable by others and can be picked up in that way? How do you do

00:12:51.599 --> 00:12:56.559
peer review of software of others? There's code review which is part of the team building practice

00:12:56.559 --> 00:13:01.760
but ROpenSci also does what we call peer review which is the practice of reviewing and giving

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:08.479
feedback to other people's code, other people's projects. How do you give effective feedback? How

00:13:08.479 --> 00:13:14.559
do you do reviewing and enter a code base that you're not familiar with so that you can provide

00:13:14.559 --> 00:13:20.880
useful information? We have sessions on contributing to other open source projects. So in our last

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:26.799
cohort we had Heather Turner who runs RDevDays for contributing to RCore itself, how people can

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:32.400
participate in that. And then we go beyond sort of these particular technical topics because we're

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:38.880
thinking about developing people as leaders within their open source communities. So we talk about

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:44.719
organizing events. If you're going to have a hackathon or bring together maintainers, hold a

00:13:44.719 --> 00:13:48.400
webinar about the thing that you're building, how do you organize an effective event? How do you do

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:53.280
public speaking at those events? How do you do communication with your team projects? You know,

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:58.640
an open source maintainer in a small project has a lot of hats to wear and we know that it goes

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:05.440
beyond just the code. How does this work in practice? Well, so the collaborative teamwork, we

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:10.960
think of collaborative first Git. Some people learn Git, say first Git's a version control system,

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:15.440
here's a bunch of Git commands and you get like the first bit, but Git is first a collaboration

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:21.200
tool and teaching it as a collaboration tool is the way we design our lessons. This is our current

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:28.159
version of that lesson, actually written by one of our first cohorts champions, Parker Ellis, and then

00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:34.239
we do peer-to-peer code review because some people join in order to develop code, some people join

00:14:34.239 --> 00:14:39.919
in order to review and practice contribution, and so we will match them up and so people are able

00:14:39.919 --> 00:14:43.840
to do that code review for each other. Those collaborative skills are what we're building.

00:14:47.119 --> 00:14:53.599
The next thing we do is this is project-based and the reason it's project-based is partially to

00:14:53.599 --> 00:14:58.080
build skills and build confidence, but it's as much for us because what we want to do

00:14:58.719 --> 00:15:04.159
is empower people as peers within our community. I'm not looking in this program to find the

00:15:04.159 --> 00:15:10.559
person who is going to do the work for my package. I am looking to develop a peer who has a project

00:15:10.559 --> 00:15:18.400
that I am interested in contributing to so that we have a mutual and equal exchange. So the projects

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:24.000
that people create are not toy projects. These are things that have lasting and important impact

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:30.320
in their open source communities. So we have a lot of participation of people from ministries

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:37.280
and national statistical agencies, from research institutions. So here's an example. We have a

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:43.359
package that is a processing package for the Argentine census data, which did not exist in a

00:15:43.359 --> 00:15:49.679
standardized form year to year prior to development, which has rapidly become an important tool in

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:58.239
Argentine population and demographic science. Similarly, tools for Brazilian transport systems.

00:15:58.719 --> 00:16:03.599
You know, we have a global project. We have an ornithology team in Taiwan that makes a great

00:16:03.599 --> 00:16:12.559
deal of use of the Taiwan-British bird survey package. So these are

00:16:12.559 --> 00:16:18.799
important projects. We're recruiting important projects as well as champions so that what they

00:16:18.799 --> 00:16:24.880
build is something that is of lasting value and attracts its own maintainers.

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:33.760
One thing we do a lot in the program is evaluate and iterate on this design to improve it. So we

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:40.000
have a great partnership with the Center for Scientific Collaboration and Community Engagement,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:44.559
and that may be the first time that I got its acronym right on the first time. Or I might have

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:49.919
gotten it wrong. I'm not sure. So every year we go back and we interview our champions and our

00:16:49.919 --> 00:16:57.280
mentors. We conduct a survey and evaluation to understand what worked and what didn't. That also

00:16:57.280 --> 00:17:03.520
enables us to collect a lot of mission that helps us communicate about the program and the program's

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:09.439
value. And what we're really trying to understand when we do these evaluations is not just did people

00:17:09.439 --> 00:17:16.400
like this? Did people's skills improve? That's nice. We want to know are communities of practice

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:24.000
forming as a result of this work? And are those communities impactful? So we ask

00:17:24.319 --> 00:17:29.920
survey questions and we ask free form questions to hear from people what they are getting out of

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:35.280
the program and what is resulting. So we have things like this. The feedback and interest

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:41.520
are received from other participants and mentors gave me the confidence and motivation to continue

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:47.359
improving it in this package. If I were wanting to transform national data into something useful

00:17:47.359 --> 00:17:52.319
for the wider public. So we're getting that community activity happening and we are getting

00:17:52.319 --> 00:17:58.719
the impact as a result of the activity. And then we interview the mentors. Because as I say,

00:17:58.719 --> 00:18:07.839
our goal is to create peers, not students or apprentices. And so what do the mentors say?

00:18:07.839 --> 00:18:11.920
Being part of a cohort makes people feel they belong to a larger community. I learned from my

00:18:11.920 --> 00:18:18.319
mentee, too. That's us accomplishing our goals. Now, the challenge of the program is we only have

00:18:18.319 --> 00:18:24.640
so many people, so many cohorts. We run two ten-person cohorts a year. There's a limit to

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:28.560
that impact. And so we want to think about how it multiplies. And so part of the design of the

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:35.839
program is in identifying and cultivating leadership in Unchampions. We select people

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:44.800
who have leadership potential in their local communities, right? And we encourage activities

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:49.920
to facilitate that. We ask everyone who participates to do something in the realm of

00:18:50.479 --> 00:18:57.439
giving a talk, running a workshop in their city, in their university, in their agency, thinking

00:18:57.439 --> 00:19:03.439
about how to bring these practices to a larger group beyond the ten people. Because we just don't

00:19:03.439 --> 00:19:08.959
want our OpenSci participants to expand our community of practice. We want to build these

00:19:08.959 --> 00:19:13.920
community of practices and networks wider, which means we have a reach into all of those places.

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:23.680
And this has been spectacular. So one of our champions founded the R User Group for Rosario

00:19:23.680 --> 00:19:29.839
in Argentina. There is now a continuous user group in that city as a result of this. We have people

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:37.680
doing international work for meetups through the international affinity groups, giving talks within

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:41.839
their agencies about how they can use these packages, how they develop, how people can

00:19:42.479 --> 00:19:49.280
contribute to them. All of those let us have the impact in creating these communities of practice

00:19:49.920 --> 00:20:01.040
well beyond the ones that we run ourselves. So this morning in the keynote, Dr. Hicks gave a

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:09.839
part of her talk where she talked about the metaphor of the plants and the soil, where

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:17.040
the developers are seeds, and the job of a manager is to cultivate the soil in which the seeds grow.

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:24.719
And I think in our context, we have a much bigger field to tend to the soil of,

00:20:25.359 --> 00:20:31.839
because what we are trying to do is not just build skills within our team,

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:39.280
but make sure that we are building the community from which our future developers,

00:20:39.280 --> 00:20:45.760
maintainers, and leaders are coming. The community of practice is the thing we have to make sure is

00:20:45.760 --> 00:20:55.119
rich and fertile for all of those accomplishes to grow out of. So that's it. I very much want to

00:20:55.119 --> 00:21:02.079
thank Shani for being the leader of this program. Within ROpenSci, Mel Simon and Stephanie Lesert

00:21:02.079 --> 00:21:08.000
are the other big participants in this program. But of course, well beyond the core RopenSci,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.640
I want to thank so much all of the champions and mentors we've had in this program over the few

00:21:12.640 --> 00:21:18.719
years. We have several of them in the room today on all sides. They're what makes the success.

00:21:19.199 --> 00:21:22.719
And that's it. Thank you all very much. I'm happy to take any questions.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:37.280
Thank you so much. We have a few questions here. So what is the typical experience of experience

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:42.000
backgrounds of folks in the ROpenSci community? Are there ways for high schoolers or college

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.959
students learning data science to get involved? I mean, there's certainly a place that the typical

00:21:46.959 --> 00:21:53.920
experience of champions tends to be early and mid-career. We have a lot of people who are like

00:21:53.920 --> 00:22:03.520
well into research or other data science career that they're in. We have had high schoolers

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:11.520
participate in ROpenSci. I think we've had a couple of examples. Our software peer review,

00:22:12.479 --> 00:22:19.599
our hackathon projects, they're all open. They're not age limited. I admit we haven't

00:22:19.599 --> 00:22:25.520
focused on youth development in it, but we have something called the contributing guide

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:32.959
at ROpenSci. So it's contributing.ropensci.org. And it's actually like a book about all of

00:22:32.959 --> 00:22:38.319
different ways to enter into the community of practice. Do you want to sign up to review?

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:43.599
Do you want to join in one of our webathons or hackathons? Do you have one of these other

00:22:43.599 --> 00:22:48.719
projects we can contribute to? Do you want to contribute to the platform? All of those

00:22:48.719 --> 00:22:53.359
things are widely open, and we do actually get a very wide range of people who participate.

00:22:54.160 --> 00:23:02.239
Great. Is ROpenSci affiliated with PyOpenSci? And do you think we're going towards a polyglot

00:23:02.239 --> 00:23:07.199
OpenSci in the future? We are very good friends. We have a joint Slack channel where we talk about

00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:13.040
collective challenges, and PyOpenSci does a lot of, they have a parallel, they have a similar

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:21.280
software review process, and they do a lot of work in the Python packaging ecosystem to harmonize

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:25.599
and document and help people understand the complexity of the Python packaging world.

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:35.760
They started about three years ago. And so I think we collaborate a lot. We're both able to

00:23:36.319 --> 00:23:41.599
do what we do because we have a lot of focused expertise within the organization about the

00:23:41.599 --> 00:23:46.719
particulars of the language and the platforms and the communities that have sprung up around.

00:23:46.719 --> 00:23:52.479
And so we've talked about, should there be one OpenSci? And we're not sure there should be,

00:23:52.479 --> 00:23:56.880
but there's a very tight loop between us. And so people who are interested in one can easily

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:02.719
move between another, and much of the design of, say, the peer review system or the philosophy of

00:24:02.719 --> 00:24:09.920
the community is really well aligned between us. Perfect. One last question here. How do we

00:24:09.920 --> 00:24:19.280
apply for the program? We will have, and we have an announcement twice or once a year. They're one

00:24:19.280 --> 00:24:27.359
year and two cohort years, depending. And we put out an announcement that in addition to our

00:24:28.319 --> 00:24:34.160
our website, as I said, we do really heavy recruitment. So we'll go out through a great

00:24:34.160 --> 00:24:41.760
many of, you will see it in Latin R and Africa R and the Japan R groups and the global R ladies

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:47.280
groups. And if you're a participant in any of those spaces, it will show up. We're able to do

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:52.800
it pretty loudly. Of course, you can also follow This Is My on our website, any of our social media,

00:24:52.800 --> 00:25:03.199
it will show up. We did our last announcement in, it was the late spring that our cohort is now doing

00:25:04.400 --> 00:25:11.119
in its first month of training for. And so I would expect the next one is probably going to be

00:25:13.040 --> 00:25:16.719
a similar time next year. I think we're going to run two cohorts next year.

00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:21.119
Sometime in mid to early spring, we'll probably have the announcement for recruiting them.

00:25:21.119 --> 00:25:28.079
Great. Thank you so much.

